Three dataframe types — keep them straight.

Once you bring the pandas interface into the picture, there are three different things all called a dataframe, and confusing them is a common mistake. Let us keep them separate.

The first is a plain pandas dataframe. Its data lives entirely in driver memory, on one machine. You use it for final-mile analysis, plotting, and small fixtures.

The second is a pandas-on-Spark dataframe. This one looks like pandas on the surface, but its data is distributed across the executors. You reach for it when you want pandas syntax but Spark scale.

The third is the native Spark dataframe. Also distributed across the executors, and it gives you the best performance and the most features.

So the first lives entirely on the driver, while the other two are distributed — same engine underneath, just a different surface. The thing that makes pandas-on-Spark special is that it lays a pandas-style index on top of a Spark dataframe.
